# {{EXTENSION_NAME}}

An [Asyar](https://github.com/Xoshbin/asyar) extension.

## Development

```bash
pnpm install      # install dependencies
pnpm run build    # production build
pnpm run dev      # watch mode (hot reload)
```

Once built, register the extension for dev loading:

```bash
asyar attach .
```

Validate your manifest before publishing:

```bash
asyar validate
```

## Publishing

```bash
asyar publish
```

## Extension architecture

This extension follows the Asyar Tier 2 bootstrap pattern:

1. **`src/main.ts`** creates a single `ExtensionContext`, calls
   `setExtensionId(id)` (which self-registers with the iframe's
   `ExtensionBridge`), and registers the extension class via
   `bridge.registerManifest` + `bridge.registerExtensionImplementation`.
   This is what lets the bridge dispatch `asyar:search:request` and
   `asyar:command:execute` messages into your extension's methods.

2. **`src/index.ts`** exports the `Extension` class with
   `initialize`, `search`, `executeCommand`, etc. The class captures
   the `ExtensionContext` reference in `initialize()` so later
   `search()` calls can read live preferences.

3. **Preferences** are declared in `manifest.json` under the
   `preferences` field. The launcher auto-generates a settings form
   in Settings → Extensions → {{EXTENSION_NAME}}. Your extension
   reads values via `context.preferences.<name>` and subscribes to
   `context.onPreferencesChanged(cb)` to react when the user edits
   them.

## Key manifest fields

| Field | Description |
|---|---|
| `asyarSdk` | Minimum SDK version required (semver range, e.g. `"^1.12.0"`) |
| `minAppVersion` | Minimum Asyar app version required (semver, e.g. `"1.0.0"`) |
| `platforms` | Restrict to specific OSes. Omit for universal. Valid values: `"macos"`, `"windows"`, `"linux"` |
| `permissions` | Declare every permission your extension uses (clipboard, network, notifications, etc.) |
| `preferences` | Typed user-configurable settings. Auto-rendered in the Extensions settings tab and injected into `context.preferences`. See [Preferences docs](https://github.com/Xoshbin/asyar/blob/main/asyar-launcher/docs/reference/sdk/preferences.md). |

## Preferences example

Preferences are declared at the manifest level (apply to the whole
extension) or at the command level (apply only to one command):

```json
{
  "preferences": [
    {
      "name": "apiKey",
      "type": "password",
      "title": "API Key",
      "description": "Encrypted at rest on this device.",
      "required": true
    },
    {
      "name": "units",
      "type": "dropdown",
      "title": "Units",
      "default": "metric",
      "data": [
        { "value": "metric", "title": "Celsius" },
        { "value": "imperial", "title": "Fahrenheit" }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

Supported types: `textfield`, `password`, `number`, `checkbox`,
`dropdown`, `appPicker`, `file`, `directory`. `password` values are
encrypted at rest with a device-local AES-256-GCM key and excluded
from cloud sync. `required: true` preferences block command execution
until the user sets a value (the launcher shows a blocking modal).

Read values in your extension:

```ts
async initialize(context: ExtensionContext) {
  this.context = context;
  const apiKey = context.preferences.apiKey as string | undefined;
}

// React to live edits:
context.onPreferencesChanged(() => {
  const freshKey = context.preferences.apiKey as string;
  // re-apply downstream state…
});
```

## Platform example

If your extension only works on macOS and Linux, add to `manifest.json`:

```json
"platforms": ["macos", "linux"]
```

Leave the field out entirely if your extension works on all platforms.
